subsubsection.p:
So the rectangle calculation says
\boxed{ \oint_{\partial R}\eta = \iint_R 2\,dA. }
The left side is a boundary integral. The right side is an area integral over the region.

For a circle of radius R, use \mathbf r(t)=(R\cos t,R\sin t), \qquad 0\le t\le2\pi. Then dx=-R\sin t\,dt, \qquad dy=R\cos t\,dt. So
-y\,dx+x\,dy \amp = -(R\sin t)(-R\sin t\,dt) + (R\cos t)(R\cos t\,dt) \amp = R^2\,dt.
Thus \boxed{ \oint_C -y\,dx+x\,dy = \int_0^{2\pi}R^2\,dt = 2\pi R^2. } But the area of the disk is \pi R^2. Again, \boxed{ \oint_C -y\,dx+x\,dy = 2\,\operatorname{Area}(\text{disk}). }
